	<title>Exercises: Find the Matrix Representing a Given Linear Map</title>
	
	
	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>For each of the linear maps specified below find the matrix representing it.</para>
		</problem>
		
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para><latex>L\from \RNr\to \RNr[2]</latex>  transforms the unit vector in <latex>\RNr</latex> into the vector <latex>(â€“5,7)</latex> in <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>.</para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer>
					<math.display>
						<latex>A = \left[\begin{array}{r} -5 \\ 7 \end{array}\right]</latex>
					</math.display>
				</answer>
				<solution.hint>
					<para><subordinate>
						<hot>Look up</hot>
						<crossref><theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_LinearMapGivesMatrix"/></crossref>
					</subordinate>
						how to find the matrix representing a given linear map</para></solution.hint>
				<solution>
					<para>We know that <latex>L\from \RNr[1]\to \RNr[2]</latex>. Therefore the matrix representing <latex>L</latex> is of type <latex>(1,2)</latex>. Its one and only column vector is</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>L(\StdBss{1}) = L(1) = (-5,7)</latex>
					</math.display>
					<para>So <latex>L</latex> is represented by the matrix</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>A = \left[\begin{array}{r} -5 \\ 7 \end{array}\right]</latex>
					</math.display>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		
		
		
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para><latex>L\from \RNr[2]\to \RNr[2]</latex> transforms the unit vectors <latex>\StdBss{1}</latex> and <latex>\StdBss{2}</latex> into the vectors <latex>(3,0)</latex> and <latex>(0,3)</latex>, respectively.</para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
A = 
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
3 & 0 \\
0 & 3
\end{array}
\right]
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
				</answer>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para><latex>L\from \RNr[3]\to \RNr[2]</latex> transforms the unit vectors <latex>\StdBss{1}</latex>, <latex>\StdBss{2}</latex>, and <latex>\StdBss{3}</latex> of <latex>\RNr[3]</latex> into the vectors <latex>(3,1)</latex>, <latex>(4,2)</latex>, and <latex>(-2,-3)</latex>, respectively</para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
A = 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
3 & 4 & -2 \\
1 & 2 & -3
\end{array}
\right]
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
				</answer>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		
		
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>L\from \RNr[1]\to \RNr[4]</latex> transforms <latex>-2</latex> into the point <latex>(2,-1,1,4)</latex>.</para></problem>
			<approach>
				<answer>
					<math.display>
						<latex>A = \left[\begin{array}{r} -1 \\ \tfrac{1}{2} \\ -\tfrac{1}{2} \\ -2 \end{array}\right]</latex>
					</math.display>
				</answer>
				<solution>
					<para>We know that <latex>L\from \RNr[1]\to \RNr[4]</latex>. Therefore the matrix representing <latex>L</latex> is of type <latex>(1,4)</latex>. Its one and only column vector is <latex>L(\StdBss{1})</latex>. To find it, we compute</para>
					
					<computation>
						<left>(2,-1,1,4)</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>L(-2)</right>
						<left></left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>L(-2\cdot \StdBss{1})</right>
						<left></left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>-2\cdot L(\StdBss{1})</right>
						<left>\frac{1}{-2}\cdot (2,-1,1,4)</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>L(\StdBss{1})</right>
					</computation>
					
					<para>So <latex>L</latex> is represented by the matrix</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>A = \left[\begin{array}{r} -1 \\ \tfrac{1}{2} \\ -\tfrac{1}{2} \\ -2 \end{array}\right]</latex>
					</math.display>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
	</exercise>
